National Recovery Month is a national observance held every September to educate Americans that substance use treatment and mental health services can enable those with mental and substance use disorders to live healthy and rewarding lives.

Now in its 31st year, Recovery Month celebrates the gains made by those living in recovery. #nationalrecoverymonth2020

If you or someone you know needs access to resources for addiction or for mental health services, Your Life Iowa is a great place to start, visit yourlifeiowa.org.

post_text: Lead poisoning happens when children have too much lead in their bodies. It’s usually caused when toddlers come in contact with lead-based paint chips or lead dust found in homes built before 1978. Lead is highly toxic and can cause developmental delays, learning difficulties, headaches and more. So, if toddlers live in or visit older homes, it’s especially important to get them tested! https://bit.ly/2E00Iei

post_text: Labor Day marks the unofficial end to summer, and you may be planning one last get-together with friends and family. If a virtual party is not in your plans, remember to lower your risks of spreading COVID-19 by keeping your gathering small and outdoors. Practice social distancing, wear a face mask when in close proximity, and wash your hands often. Also, offer disposable plates and silverware and follow food safety guidelines. Have a great weekend! Coronavirus.iowa.gov

The Disaster Supplemental Nutrition Program (D-SNAP) application sites will open tomorrow, August 31, in Linn County and will be open through September 6.

If your household was adversely affected by the August 10 derecho, including food being destroyed/spoiled, you may be eligible to receive assistance. For more information, visit https://dhs.iowa.gov/d_snap
shared_text:
Iowa Department of Human Services
August 30 at 5:11 PM ·

Our Disaster Supplemental Nutrition Program (D-SNAP) application sites will open tomorrow, August 31, in Linn County and will be open through September 6. If your household was adversely affected by the August 10 derecho, including food being destroyed/spoiled, you may be eligible to receive assistance. To keep wait times to a minimum, DHS is asking applicants to apply at the site of their choosing, but to follow the schedule on our website based on the first letter of last names. We ask applicants whose last names begin with the letters A-D to apply at one of the three sites on August 31.

View full details including eligibility, application and site processing information on the DHS website here https://dhs.iowa.gov/d_snap.

post_text: Drink plenty of water and limit your time outdoors this week when it's hot. If outside, stay in the shade and wear sunscreen and protective clothing.
shared_text:
US National Weather Service Des Moines Iowa
August 24 at 5:35 AM ·

🥵🥵🥵 A prolonged stretch of unseasonable heat has settled in and will persist for multiple days this week. Each day through Thursday will see temperatures climbing well into the 90s, and possibly even approaching 100 degrees at times.

Given the persistence and duration of the heat wave, there may be a cumulative health risk especially for vulnerable populations. Please drink plenty of water and limit time spent outside if possible. When outdoors try to stay in the shade and wear sunscreen and protective clothing!

A cool front will cross Iowa late in the week, on Thursday night or Friday, bringing more seasonable conditions for next weekend as well as a return of rain and thunderstorm chances.

Stay informed! For local forecast information: weather.gov/desmoines

August 14 at 5:59 PM ·

The aftermath of the storm on August 10 has caused stress for many Iowans who are already struggling. If you or someone you know is in need of mental health services or someone to talk to, there are resources in place to help:

•Locate your regional Mental Health and Disability Services providers here - https://yourlifeiowa.org/mental-health/mhds-regions

• AbbeHealth provides mental health and has multiple facilities in Eastern Iowa - https://www.unitypoint.org/cedarrapids/locations-1.aspx

• Your Life Iowa provides information and referral, counseling, crisis service coordination, and linkages to crisis screening and mental health services 24 hours a day - https://yourlifeiowa.org/mental-health/crisis-services

•Iowa Disaster Behavioral Health Response Team is a trained team of volunteers who can mobilize resources to provide post-disaster mental health services statewide, learn more here - http://www.iowadbhrt.org/

post_text: We hope everyone stayed safe during yesterday's severe weather. As you work to make repairs and remove debris, don't forget to also clean out your refrigerator if you lost power for more than four hours. Throw away any meats, dairy, fish, eggs, or anything that has a bad odor, color, or texture. Check your freezer's food if the electricity is out for more than 48 hours and it's filled to capacity. Half-full freezers must be assessed after 24 hours. When in doubt, throw it out! https://bit.ly/2F5Gmkk

post_text: Wearing a seat belt is safe for pregnant women and is the best way to protect yourself and your baby during a car accident. https://zerofatalitiesiowa.com/buckleup.aspx
shared_text:
Iowa Department of Transportation
August 5 at 11:07 AM ·

Pregnant? Buckling up can save both you and your unborn baby in the event of a crash. Keep the shoulder belt away from your neck, but not off your shoulder. The lap belt should be secured below your belly so that it fits snugly across your hips and pelvic bone. Sit as far away from the dash as you can and make sure you keep those airbags turned on. Airbags are designed to work with seat belts, not replace them. If you are in a crash, even a minor one, call your doctor right away. Find out more at https://zerofatalitiesiowa.com/buckleup.aspx

Happy World Breastfeeding Week and National Breastfeeding Month! Breastfeeding significantly impacts the health and wellbeing of mothers and babies, both in the short and long term. Breast milk provides important nutrients, vitamins, antibodies, and other elements to keep babies healthy. Mothers that breastfeed have lower risk of breast and ovarian cancers, type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular disease including high blood pressure and high cholesterol, and rheumatoid arthritis.

For more information on breastfeeding, visit https://idph.iowa.gov/wic/breastfeeding.

post_text: Salmonella illness is more common in the summer. Warmer weather and unrefrigerated foods create ideal conditions for Salmonella to grow. Be sure to refrigerate or freeze perishables (foods likely to spoil or go bad quickly), prepared foods, and leftovers within 2 hours. Chill them within 1 hour if the temperature is 90°F or hotter.

shared_text:
Hy-Vee (1005 E Hickman Rd, Waukee, IA)
May 25 at 9:18 AM ·

Iowa Customers: In partnership with the Iowa Department of Public Health, we will be distributing 75,000 Hanes masks to the general public on Tuesday, May 26, starting at 7 A.M. at all of our Hy-Vee grocery stores and Hy-Vee Drugstores in Iowa. post_text: Thank you for your service!
shared_text:
Iowa Department of Veterans Affairs
May 6 at 11:08 AM ·

Welcome to the Iowa Vietnam Veterans Recognition Day, 2020, virtual ceremony. While the COVID-19 pandemic prevented our usual annual ceremony, and related restrictions disrupted plans to host a live broadcast of a virtual ceremony, we promised to ‘adapt and overcome,’ ensuring the day would not go unrecognized. The following multi-media presentation includes some visual highlights in our usual ceremony, and the script that was planned, including remarks from our keynote speaker Brig. Gen. Thompson, and Gov. Reynolds. We know this is no substitute for the camaraderie of our usual gathering, but these are extraordinary times, and with everyone’s help, we will return to normalcy for our next event. We invite you to watch and read, and maintain our faith that even in these times, our comrades ‘Are Not Forgotten.’
text:
Thank you for your service!

Iowa Department of Veterans Affairs
May 6 at 11:08 AM ·

Welcome to the Iowa Vietnam Veterans Recognition Day, 2020, virtual ceremony. While the COVID-19 pandemic prevented our usual annual ceremony, and related restrictions disrupted plans to host a live broadcast of a virtual ceremony, we promised to ‘adapt and overcome,’ ensuring the day would not go unrecognized. The following multi-media presentation includes some visual highlights in our usual ceremony, and the script that was planned, including remarks from our keynote speaker Brig. Gen. Thompson, and Gov. Reynolds. We know this is no substitute for the camaraderie of our usual gathering, but these are extraordinary times, and with everyone’s help, we will return to normalcy for our next event. We invite you to watch and read, and maintain our faith that even in these times, our comrades ‘Are Not Forgotten.’

post_text: IDPH Rumor Control: Beware of any social media post that offers tips or cures for COVID-19. For example, IDPH can confirm gargling with salt water and/or mouth wash does not "eliminate" the virus. There ARE simple ways, however, to slow the spread, and protect yourself and others: stay home as much as possible, avoid groups of people and keep a 6-foot distance from other individuals, even when outside or at home. More questions? Call 2-1-1.

post_text: The novel coronavirus has infected nearly 1,000 people worldwide and killed nearly 30. Influenza rarely gets this sort of attention, even though it kills more Americans each year than any other virus. In 2018, which brought the worst flu season in about 40 years, 80,000 people in the US died of the illness. Flu season can last through March and it’s not too late to get your flu shot!

post_text: Rumor control: There are no cases of novel coronavirus in Iowa. It's important to know that there are seven coronaviruses that infect humans - four of them are common and most people will get one or more in their lives - they usually cause symptoms like a cold. The novel coronavirus (the one associated with China) has not been confirmed in Iowa and the risk to Iowans is currently low.

post_text: Every year, over 18,000 Iowans are diagnosed with cancer – that’s over 300 buses full of people. Nearly 150,000 Iowans are cancer survivors. IDPH works to increase cancer screening rates, especially among low-income, uninsured and underinsured Iowans. Learn more and find links to screening resources at http://bit.ly/2uKCqR0.

post_text: Many services are available for Iowans with substance use disorder or gambling problems, yet only a small percentage use them. About 1 in 10 Iowans who could benefit from substance use disorder treatment seek help and only 1 in 100 look for help with problem gambling. Help is free, confidential and available by phone, text or online chat. Visit yourlifeiowa.org.

post_text: Breastfed babies are less likely to be sick from diarrhea, allergies and infections, and have a reduced risk of SIDS and obesity. Moms who breastfeed also benefit. They have a lower risk for breast and ovarian cancers – yet less than half of all babies at 3 months of age are breastfed in Iowa. Support a breastfeeding mom!

post_text: Falls are the second leading cause of injury death sin Iowa for all age groups, and the leading cause of injury hospitalizations and emergency visits. IDPH supports falls prevention strategies, including Tai Chi for Arthritis and Falls Prevention classes. A workshop for those interested in being a certified instructor for these classes will be held February 1-2 in Des Moines. Learn more at http://bit.ly/35LRQkz.

post_text: Radon is a naturally occurring gas that can have a big impact on indoor air quality and your health. You can't see or smell it, and radon can build up inside homes, buildings and schools to dangerous levels. Average indoor radon concentrations in Iowa are more than six times the national average! Learn more with this short video.
